# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: gptq-quantization
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] In computer architecture, **8-bit** integers or other data units are those that are 8 bits wide (1 octet).
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Also, 8-bit central processing unit (CPU) and arithmetic logic unit (ALU) architectures are those that are based on registers or data buses of that size.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Memory addresses (and thus address buses) for 8-bit CPUs are generally larger than 8-bit, usually 16-bit.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] 8-bit microcomputers are microcomputers that use 8-bit microprocessors.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The term '8-bit' is also applied to the character sets that could be used on computers with 8-bit bytes, the best known being various forms of extended ASCII, including the ISO/IEC 8859 series of national character sets – especially Latin 1 for English and Western European languages.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The IBM System/360 introduced byte-addressable memory with 8-bit bytes, as opposed to bit-addressable or decimal digit-addressable or word-addressable memory, although its general-purpose registers were 32 bits wide, and addresses were contained in the lower 24 bits of those addresses.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Different models of System/360 had different internal data path widths; the IBM System/360 Model 30 (1965) implemented the 32-bit System/360 architecture, but had an 8-bit native path width, and performed 32-bit arithmetic 8 bits at a time.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The first widely adopted 8-bit microprocessor was the Intel 8080, being used in many hobbyist computers of the late 1970s and early 1980s, often running the CP/M operating system; it had 8-bit data words and 16-bit addresses.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The Zilog Z80 (compatible with the 8080) and the Motorola 6800 were also used in similar computers.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The Z80 and the MOS Technology 6502 8-bit CPUs were widely used in home computers and second- and third-generation game consoles of the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Many 8-bit CPUs or microcontrollers are the basis of today's ubiquitous embedded systems.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] 8-bit microprocessors were the first widely used microprocessors in the computing industry, marking a major shift from mainframes and minicomputers to smaller, more affordable systems.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The introduction of 8-bit processors in the 1970s enabled the production of personal computers, leading to the popularization of computing and setting the foundation for the modern computing landscape.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The 1976 Zilog Z80, one of the most popular 8-bit CPUs (though with 4-bit ALU, at least in the original), was discontinued in 2024 (its product line Z84C00), with Last Time Buy (LTB) orders by 14 June 2024.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] An 8-bit register can store 28 different values.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The range of integer values that can be stored in 8 bits depends on the integer representation used.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] With the two most common representations, the range is 0 through 255 (28 − 1) for representation as an (unsigned) binary number, and −128 (−1 × 27) through 127 (27 − 1) for representation as two's complement.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] 8-bit CPUs use an 8-bit data bus and can therefore access 8 bits of data in a single machine instruction.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The address bus is typically a double octet (16 bits) wide, due to practical and economical considerations.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] This implies a direct address space of 64 KB (65,536 bytes) on most 8-bit processors.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Most home computers from the 8-bit era fully exploited the address space, such as the BBC Micro (Model B) with 32 KB of RAM plus 32 KB of ROM.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The Commodore 128, and other 8-bit systems, meaning still with 16-bit addressing, could use more than 64 KB, i.e.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] 128 KB RAM, also the BBC Master with it expandable to 512 KB of RAM.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Some index registers, such as the two in the 6502, are 8-bit.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] This limits the size of the arrays addressed using indexed addressing instructions to objects of up to 256 bytes (28 bytes) without requiring more complicated code.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Other 8-bit CPUs, such as the Motorola 6800 and Intel 8080, have 16-bit index registers.*"Interview with William Mensch, 1995 October 09".
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] *Silicon Genesis: Oral Histories of Semiconductor Technology*.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The first commercial 8-bit processor was the Intel 8008 (1972) which was originally intended for the Datapoint 2200 intelligent terminal.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Most competitors to Intel started off with such character oriented 8-bit microprocessors.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Modernized variants of these 8-bit machines are still one of the most common types of processor in embedded systems.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] The MOS Technology 6502, and variants of it, were used in personal computers, such as the Apple I, Apple II, Atari 8-bit computers, BBC Micro, PET, VIC-20, and in home video game consoles such as the Atari 2600 and the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] 8-bit processors continue to be designed for general education about computer hardware, as well as for hobbyists' interests.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] One such CPU was designed and implemented using 7400-series integrated circuits on a breadboard.
[src:gptq-quantization/8-bit-computing] Designing 8-bit CPUs and their respective assemblers is a common training exercise for engineering students, engineers, and hobbyists.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Almost all modern uses follow the IEEE 754-2008 standard, where the 16-bit base-2 format is referred to as **binary16**, and the exponent uses 5 bits.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] This can express values in the range ±65,504, with the minimum value above 1 being 1 + 1/1024.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Several earlier 16-bit floating point formats have existed including that of Hitachi's HD61810 DSP of 1982 (a 4-bit exponent and a 12-bit mantissa), the top 16 bits of a 32-bit float (8 exponent and 7 mantissa bits) called a bfloat16, and Thomas J.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Scott's WIF of 1991 (5 exponent bits, 10 mantissa bits) and the 3dfx Voodoo Graphics processor of 1995 (same as Hitachi).
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] ILM was searching for an image format that could handle a wide dynamic range, but without the hard drive and memory cost of single or double precision floating point.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The hardware-accelerated programmable shading group led by John Airey at SGI (Silicon Graphics) used the s10e5 data type in 1997 as part of the "bali" design effort.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] This is described in a SIGGRAPH 2000 paper (see section 4.3) and further documented in US patent 7518615.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] It was popularized by its use in the open-source OpenEXR image format.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Nvidia and Microsoft defined the **half** datatype in the Cg language, released in early 2002, and implemented it in silicon in the GeForce FX, released in late 2002.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] However, hardware support for accelerated 16-bit floating point was later dropped by Nvidia before being reintroduced in the Tegra X1 mobile GPU in 2015.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The F16C extension in 2012 allows x86 processors to convert half-precision floats to and from single-precision floats with a machine instruction.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The format is assumed to have an implicit lead bit with value 1 unless the exponent field is stored with all zeros.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Thus, only 10 bits of the significand appear in the memory format but the total precision is 11 bits.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] In IEEE 754 parlance, there are 10 bits of significand, but there are 11 bits of significand precision (log10(211) ≈ 3.311 decimal digits, or 4 digits ± slightly less than 5 units in the last place).
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The half-precision binary floating-point exponent is encoded using an offset-binary representation, with the zero offset being 15; also known as exponent bias in the IEEE 754 standard.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Thus, as defined by the offset binary representation, in order to get the true exponent the offset of 15 has to be subtracted from the stored exponent.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The stored exponents 000002 and 111112 are interpreted specially.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The minimum strictly positive (subnormal) value is 2−24 ≈ 5.96 × 10−8.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The minimum positive normal value is 2−14 ≈ 6.10 × 10−5.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] These examples are given in bit representation of the floating-point value.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] This includes the sign bit, (biased) exponent, and significand.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] By default, 1/3 rounds down like for double precision, because of the odd number of bits in the significand.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The bits beyond the rounding point are 0101... which is less than 1/2 of a unit in the last place.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] ARM processors support (via a floating-point control register bit) an "alternative half-precision" format, which does away with the special case for an exponent value of 31 (111112).
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] It is almost identical to the IEEE format, but there is no encoding for infinity or NaNs; instead, an exponent of 31 encodes normalized numbers in the range 65536 to 131008.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Half precision is used in several computer graphics environments to store pixels, including MATLAB, OpenEXR, JPEG XR, GIMP, OpenGL, Vulkan, Cg, Direct3D, and D3DX.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The advantage over 8-bit or 16-bit integers is that the increased dynamic range allows for more detail to be preserved in highlights and shadows for images, and avoids gamma correction.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The advantage over 32-bit single-precision floating point is that it requires half the storage and bandwidth (at the expense of precision and range).
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Half precision can be useful for mesh quantization.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Mesh data is usually stored using 32-bit single-precision floats for the vertices, however in some situations it is acceptable to reduce the precision to only 16-bit half-precision, requiring only half the storage at the expense of some precision.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Mesh quantization can also be done with 8-bit or 16-bit fixed precision depending on the requirements.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Hardware and software for machine learning and neural networks often use half-precision arithmetic to accelerate computations.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] In these applications, the distinct bfloat16 format is sometimes preferred for its wider dynamic range than half-precision, and specialized floating point formats with only 8 bits or less are increasingly used to further accelerate certain computations.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] If the hardware has instructions to compute half-precision math, it is often faster than single or double precision, sometimes up to 4 times faster.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] In addition if the system has SIMD instructions, often one instruction can simultaneously operate on twice as many half values than float values.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Zig, Odin, and other languages provide support for half precisions with their `f16` type.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] .NET 5 introduced half precision floating point numbers with the `System.Half` standard library type.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] As of 16 July 2025, no .NET language (C#, F#, Visual Basic, and C++/CLI and C++/CX) has literals (e.g. in C#, `1.0f` has type `System.Single` or `1.0m` has type `System.Decimal`) or a keyword for the type.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Swift introduced half-precision floating point numbers in Swift 5.3 with the `Float16` type.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] OpenCL also supports half-precision floating point numbers with the half datatype on IEEE 754-2008 half-precision storage format.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] As of 31 May 2026, Rust is currently working on adding a new `f16` type for IEEE half-precision 16-bit floats.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Julia provides support for half-precision floating point numbers with the `Float16` type.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] C++ introduced half-precision since C++23 with the `std::float16_t` type.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Several versions of the ARM architecture have support for half precision.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Support for conversions with half-precision floats in the x86 instruction set is specified in the F16C instruction set extension, first introduced in 2009 by AMD and fairly broadly adopted by AMD and Intel CPUs by 2012.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] This was further extended up the AVX-512_FP16 instruction set extension implemented in the Intel Sapphire Rapids processor.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] On RISC-V, the `Zfh` and `Zfhmin` extensions provide hardware support for 16-bit half precision floats.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] The `Zfhmin` extension is a minimal alternative to `Zfh`.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] On Power ISA, VSX and the not-yet-approved SVP64 extension provide hardware support for 16-bit half-precision floats as of PowerISA v3.1B and later.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] Support for half precision on IBM Z is part of the Neural-network-processing-assist facility that IBM introduced with Telum.
[src:gptq-quantization/half-precision-floating-point-format] IBM refers to half precision floating point data as NNP-Data-Type 1 (16-bit).
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A **large language model** (**LLM**) is a neural network trained on a vast amount of text for natural language processing tasks, especially language generation.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can typically generate, summarize, translate, and analyze text in many contexts, and are a foundational technology behind modern chatbots.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Biased or inaccurate training data can make an LLM's output less reliable.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are typically based on transformer architecture.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Generative pre-trained transformers (GPTs) are a type of LLM that is pre-trained to predict the next word.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] GPTs are then often fine-tuned to follow instructions and to behave as assistants.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Benchmark evaluations for LLMs attempt to measure model reasoning, factual accuracy, alignment, and safety.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Before the emergence of transformer-based models in 2017, some language models were considered large relative to the computational and data constraints of their time.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the early 1990s, IBM's statistical models pioneered word alignment techniques for machine translation, laying the groundwork for corpus-based language modeling.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2001, a smoothed *n*-gram model, such as those employing Kneser–Ney smoothing, trained on 300 million words, achieved state-of-the-art perplexity on benchmark tests.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] During the 2000s, with the rise of widespread internet access, researchers began compiling massive text datasets from the web ("web as corpus") to train statistical language models.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Moving beyond *n*-gram models, researchers started in 2000 to use neural networks as language models.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Following the breakthrough of deep neural networks in image classification around 2012, similar architectures were adapted for language tasks.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This shift was marked by the development of word embeddings (e.g., Word2Vec by Mikolov in 2013) and sequence-to-sequence (seq2seq) models using LSTM.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2016, Google transitioned its translation service to neural machine translation (NMT), replacing statistical phrase-based models with deep recurrent neural networks.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These early NMT systems used LSTM-based encoder-decoder architectures, as they preceded the invention of transformers.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] At the 2017 NeurIPS conference, Google researchers introduced the transformer architecture in their landmark paper "Attention Is All You Need".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This paper's goal was to improve upon 2014 seq2seq technology, and was based mainly on the attention mechanism developed by Bahdanau et al. in 2014.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The following year in 2018, BERT was introduced and quickly became "ubiquitous".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Though the original transformer has both encoder and decoder blocks, BERT is an encoder-only model.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Academic and research usage of BERT began to decline in 2023, following rapid improvements in the abilities of decoder-only models (such as GPT) to solve tasks via prompting.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Although decoder-only GPT-1 was introduced in 2018, it was GPT-2 in 2019 that caught widespread attention because OpenAI claimed to have initially deemed it too powerful to release publicly, out of fear of malicious use.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] GPT-3 in 2020 went a step further and as of 2025 is available only via API with no offering of downloading the model to execute locally.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] But it was the consumer-facing chatbot ChatGPT in late 2022 that received extensive media coverage and public attention by 2023.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The 2023 GPT-4 was praised for its increased accuracy and as a "holy grail" for its multimodal capabilities.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI did not reveal the high-level architecture and the number of parameters of GPT-4.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The release of ChatGPT led to an uptick in LLM usage across several research subfields of computer science, including robotics, software engineering, and societal impact work.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2024, OpenAI released the reasoning model OpenAI o1, which generates long chains of thought before returning a final answer.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Many LLMs with parameter counts comparable to those of OpenAI's GPT series have been developed.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Since 2022, weights-available models have been gaining popularity, especially at first with BLOOM and LLaMA, though both have restrictions on usage and deployment.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Mistral AI's open-weight models Mistral 7B and Mixtral 8x7B have a more permissive Apache License.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, DeepSeek released DeepSeek R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight model that performs comparably to OpenAI o1 but at a much lower price per token for users.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Since 2023, many LLMs have been trained to be multimodal, having the ability to also process or generate other types of data, such as images, audio, or 3D meshes.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Open-weight LLMs have become more influential since 2023.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] (2025), community-driven contributions to open-weight models improve their efficiency and performance via collaborative platforms such as Hugging Face.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As machine learning algorithms process numbers rather than text, the text must be converted to numbers.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, a vocabulary is decided upon, then integer indices are arbitrarily but uniquely assigned to each vocabulary entry, and finally, an embedding is associated with the integer index.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Algorithms include byte-pair encoding (BPE) and WordPiece.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] There are also special tokens serving as control characters, such as `[MASK]` for masked-out token (as used in BERT), and `[UNK]` ("unknown") for characters not appearing in the vocabulary.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Also, some special symbols are used to denote special text formatting.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, "Ġ" denotes a preceding whitespace in RoBERTa and GPT and "##" denotes continuation of a preceding word in BERT.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Tokenization also compresses the datasets.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Because LLMs generally require input to be an array that is not jagged, the shorter texts must be "padded" until they match the length of the longest one.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As an example, consider a tokenizer based on byte-pair encoding.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the first step, all unique characters (including blanks and punctuation marks) are treated as an initial set of *n*-grams (i.e. initial set of uni-grams).
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Successively the most frequent pair of adjacent characters is merged into a bi-gram and all instances of the pair are replaced by it.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] All occurrences of adjacent pairs of (previously merged) *n*-grams that most frequently occur together are then again merged into even lengthier *n*-gram, until a vocabulary of prescribed size is obtained.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] After a tokenizer is trained, any text can be tokenized by it, as long as it does not contain characters not appearing in the initial-set of uni-grams.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the context of training LLMs, datasets are typically cleaned by removing low-quality, duplicated, or toxic data.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Cleaned datasets can increase training efficiency and lead to improved downstream performance.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A trained LLM can be used to clean datasets for training a further LLM.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] With the increasing proportion of LLM-generated content on the web, data cleaning in the future may include filtering out such content.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLM-generated content can pose a problem if the content is similar to human text (making filtering difficult) but of lower quality (degrading performance of models trained on it).
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Training of largest language models might need more linguistic data than naturally available, or that the naturally occurring data is of insufficient quality.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In these cases, synthetic data might be used.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is a type of foundation model (large X model) trained on language.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In particular, GPT models are first pretrained to predict the next word on a large amount of data, before being fine-tuned.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Substantial infrastructure is necessary for training the largest models.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The tendency towards larger models is visible in the list of large language models.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, the training of GPT-2 (i.e. a 1.5-billion-parameter model) in 2019 cost $50,000, while training of the PaLM (i.e. a 540-billion-parameter model) in 2022 cost $8 million, and Megatron-Turing NLG 530B (in 2021) cost around $11 million.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The qualifier "large" in "large language model" is inherently vague, as there is no definitive threshold for the number of parameters required to qualify as "large".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Before being fine-tuned, most LLMs are next-token predictors.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The fine-tuning shapes the LLM's behavior via techniques like reinforcement learning from human feedback (RLHF) or constitutional AI.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Instruction fine-tuning is a form of supervised learning used to teach LLMs to follow user instructions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2022, OpenAI demonstrated InstructGPT, a version of GPT-3 similarly fine-tuned to follow instructions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] RLHF involves training a reward model to predict which text humans prefer.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Then, the LLM can be fine-tuned through reinforcement learning to better satisfy this reward model.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Since humans typically prefer truthful, helpful and harmless answers, RLHF favors such answers.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs are generally based on the transformer architecture, which leverages an attention mechanism that enables the model to process relationships between all elements in a sequence simultaneously, regardless of their distance from each other.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] (2023) proposed state-space representation models as an alternative.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] 117M parameter sized) GPT-2 model has had twelve attention heads and a context window of only 1k tokens.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A mixture of experts (MoE) is a machine learning architecture in which multiple specialized neural networks ("experts") work together, with a gating mechanism that routes each input to the most appropriate expert(s).
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Mixtures of experts can reduce inference costs, as only a fraction of the parameters are used for each input.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Typically, LLMs are trained with single or half-precision floating point numbers (float32 and float16).
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] One float16 has 16 bits, or 2 bytes, and so one billion parameters require 2 gigabytes.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The largest models typically have more than 100 billion parameters, which places them outside the range of most consumer electronics.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] It is possible to fine-tune quantized models using low-rank adaptation.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Beyond basic text generation, various techniques have been developed to extend LLM capabilities, including the use of external tools and data sources, improved reasoning on complex problems, and enhanced instruction-following or autonomy through prompting methods.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2020, OpenAI researchers demonstrated that their new model GPT-3 could understand what format to use given a few rounds of Q and A (or other type of task) in the input data as example, thanks in part due to the RLHF technique.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This technique, called *few-shot prompting*, allows LLMs to be adapted to any task without requiring fine-tuning.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Also in 2022, it was found that the base GPT-3 model can generate an instruction based on user input.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The generated instruction along with user input is then used as input to another instance of the model under a "Instruction: [...], Input: [...], Output:" format.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The other instance is able to complete the output and often produces the correct answer in doing so.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The ability to "self-instruct" makes LLMs able to bootstrap themselves toward a correct answer.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can be turned into a chatbot by specializing it for conversation.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] User input is prefixed with a marker such as "Q:" or "User:" and the LLM is asked to predict the output after a fixed "A:" or "Assistant:".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This type of model became commercially available in 2022 with ChatGPT, a sibling model of InstructGPT fine-tuned to accept and produce dialog-formatted text based on GPT-3.5.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] It could similarly follow user instructions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Before the stream of User and Assistant lines, a chat context usually starts with a few lines of overarching instructions, from a role called "developer" or "system" to convey a higher authority than the user's input.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) is an approach that integrates LLMs with document retrieval systems.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Given a query, a document retriever is called to retrieve the most relevant documents.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This is usually done by encoding the query and the documents into vectors, then finding the documents with vectors (usually stored in a vector database) most similar to the vector of the query.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The LLM then generates an output based on both the query and context included from the retrieved documents.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Tool use is a mechanism that enables LLMs to interact with external systems, applications, or data sources.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] It can allow LLMs to, for example, fetch real-time information from an API or to execute code.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A program separate from the LLM watches the output stream of the LLM for a special tool-calling syntax.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] When these special tokens appear, the program calls the tool accordingly and feeds its output back into the LLM's input stream.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Early tool-using LLMs were fine-tuned on the use of specific tools.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] But fine-tuning LLMs for the ability to read API documentation and call APIs correctly has greatly expanded the range of tools accessible to an LLM.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is typically not an autonomous agent by itself, as it lacks the ability to interact with dynamic environments, recall past behaviors, and plan future actions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] But it can be transformed into an agent by adding supporting elements: the role (profile) and the surrounding environment of an agent can be additional inputs to the LLM, while memory can be integrated as a tool or provided as additional input.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Instructions and input patterns are used to make the LLM plan actions and tool use is used to potentially carry out these actions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In the DEPS ("describe, explain, plan and select") method, an LLM is first connected to the visual world via image descriptions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] It is then prompted to produce plans for complex tasks and behaviors based on its pretrained knowledge and the environmental feedback it receives.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The *Reflexion method* constructs an agent that learns over multiple episodes.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] At the end of each episode, the LLM is given the record of the episode, and prompted to think up "lessons learned", which would help it perform better at a subsequent episode.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These "lessons learned" are stored as a form of long-term memory and given to the agent in the subsequent episodes.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Monte Carlo tree search can use an LLM as rollout heuristic.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] When a programmatic world model is not available, an LLM can also be prompted with a description of the environment to act as world model.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Multiple agents with memory can interact socially.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A 2022 paper demonstrated a separate technique called *chain-of-thought prompting*, which makes the LLM break the question down autonomously.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM is given some examples where the "assistant" verbally breaks down the thought process before arriving at an answer.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The LLM mimics these examples and also tries to spend some time generating intermediate steps before providing the final answer.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This additional step elicited by prompting improves the correctness of the LLM on relatively complex questions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] On math word questions, a prompted model can exceed even fine-tuned GPT-3 with a verifier.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Chain-of-thought can also be elicited by simply adding an instruction like "Let's think step by step" to the prompt, in order to encourage the LLM to proceed methodically instead of trying to directly guess the answer.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In late 2024, a new approach to LLM development emerged with "reasoning models".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These are trained to generate step-by-step analysis before producing final answers, enabling better results on complex tasks, for instance in mathematics, coding and logic.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] OpenAI introduced this concept with their o1 model in September 2024, followed by o3 in April 2025.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] On the International Mathematics Olympiad qualifying exam problems, GPT-4o achieved 13% accuracy while o1 reached 83%.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In January 2025, the Chinese company DeepSeek released DeepSeek-R1, a 671-billion-parameter open-weight reasoning model that achieved comparable performance to OpenAI's o1 while being significantly more cost-effective to operate.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Unlike proprietary models from OpenAI, DeepSeek-R1's open-weight nature allowed researchers to study and build upon the algorithm, though its training data remained private.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These reasoning models typically require more computational resources per query compared to traditional LLMs, as they perform more extensive processing to work through problems step by step.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Multimodality means having multiple modalities, where a "modality" refers to a type of input or output, such as video, image, audio, text, proprioception, etc.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, Google PaLM model was fine-tuned into a multimodal model and applied to robotic control.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLaMA models have also been turned multimodal using the tokenization method, to allow image inputs, and video inputs.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] GPT-4o can process and generate text, audio and images.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A common method to create multimodal models out of an LLM is to "tokenize" the output of a trained encoder.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Concretely, one can construct an LLM that can understand images as follows: take a trained LLM, and take a trained image encoder E .
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Make a small multilayer perceptron f , so that for any image y , the post-processed vector $f(E(y))$ has the same dimensions as an encoded token.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Then, one can interleave text tokens and image tokens.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The compound model is then fine-tuned on an image-text dataset.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This basic construction can be applied with more sophistication to improve the model.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The image encoder may be frozen to improve stability.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This type of method, where embeddings from multiple modalities are fused and the predictor is trained on the combined embeddings, is called *early fusion*.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Another method, called *intermediate fusion*, involves each modality being first processed independently to obtain modality-specific representations; then these intermediate representations are fused together.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In general, cross-attention is used for integrating information from different modalities.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As an example, the Flamingo model uses cross-attention layers to inject visual information into its pre-trained language model.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can handle programming languages similarly to how they handle natural languages.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] No special change in token handling is needed as code, like human language, is represented as plain text.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs can generate code based on problems or instructions written in natural language.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] They can also describe code in natural language or translate it into other programming languages.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] They were originally used as a code completion tool, but advances have moved them towards automatic programming.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Services such as GitHub Copilot offer LLMs specifically trained, fine-tuned, or prompted for programming.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In computational biology, transformer-based architectures, such as DNA LLMs, have also proven useful in analyzing biological sequences: protein, DNA, and RNA.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] With proteins they appear able to capture a degree of "grammar" from the amino-acid sequence, by mapping that sequence into an embedding.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] On tasks such as structure prediction and mutational outcome prediction, a small model using an embedding as input can approach or exceed much larger models using multiple sequence alignments (MSA) as input.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] ESMFold, Meta Platforms' embedding-based method for protein structure prediction, runs an order of magnitude faster than AlphaFold2 thanks to the removal of an MSA requirement and a lower parameter count due to the use of embeddings.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Meta hosts ESM Atlas, a database of 772 million structures of metagenomic proteins predicted using ESMFold.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] An LLM can also design proteins unlike any seen in nature.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Nucleic acid models have proven useful in detecting regulatory sequences, sequence classification, RNA-RNA interaction prediction, and RNA structure prediction.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Performance of bigger models on various tasks, when plotted on a log-log scale, appears as a linear extrapolation of performance achieved by smaller models.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] However, this linearity may be punctuated by "break(s)" in the scaling law, where the slope of the line changes abruptly, and where larger models acquire "emergent abilities".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] They arise from the complex interaction of the model's components and are not explicitly programmed or designed.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Schaeffer *et al.* argue that the emergent abilities are not unpredictably acquired, but predictably acquired according to a smooth scaling law.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The authors considered a toy statistical model of an LLM solving multiple-choice questions, and showed that this statistical model, modified to account for other types of tasks, applies to these tasks as well.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Let x be the number of parameter count, and y be the performance of the model.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability seeks to precisely identify and understand how individual neurons or circuits within LLMs produce specific behaviors or outputs.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] By reverse-engineering model components at a granular level, researchers aim to detect and mitigate safety concerns such as emergent harmful behaviors, biases, deception, or unintended goal pursuit before deployment.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Mechanistic interpretability research has been conducted at organizations like Anthropic and OpenAI, although understanding the inner workings of LLMs remains difficult.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The reverse-engineering may lead to the discovery of algorithms that approximate inferences performed by an LLM.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For instance, the authors trained small transformers on modular arithmetic addition.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The resulting models were reverse-engineered, and it turned out they used discrete Fourier transform.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The training of the model also highlighted a phenomenon called grokking, in which the model initially memorizes the training set (overfitting), and later suddenly learns to actually perform the calculation.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] NLP researchers were evenly split when asked, in a 2022 survey, whether (untuned) LLMs "could (ever) understand natural language in some nontrivial sense".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Proponents of "LLM understanding" believe that some LLM abilities, such as mathematical reasoning, imply an ability to "understand" certain concepts.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Some researchers characterize LLMs as "alien intelligence".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, Conjecture CEO Connor Leahy considers untuned LLMs to be like inscrutable alien "Shoggoths", and believes that RLHF tuning creates a "smiling facade" obscuring the inner workings of the LLM: "If you don't push it too far, the smiley face stays on.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In contrast, some skeptics of LLM understanding believe that existing LLMs are "simply remixing and recombining existing writing", a phenomenon known as stochastic parrot, or they point to the deficits existing LLMs continue to have in prediction skills, reasoning skills, agency, and explainability.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, GPT-4 has natural deficits in planning and in real-time learning.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Generative LLMs have been observed to confidently assert claims of fact which do not seem to be justified by their training data, a phenomenon which has been termed "hallucination".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Specifically, hallucinations in the context of LLMs correspond to the generation of text or responses that seem syntactically sound, fluent, and natural but are factually incorrect, nonsensical, or unfaithful to the provided source input.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Neuroscientist Terrence Sejnowski has argued that "The diverging opinions of experts on the intelligence of LLMs suggests that our old ideas based on natural intelligence are inadequate".
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Efforts to reduce or compensate for hallucinations have employed automated reasoning, retrieval-augmented generation (RAG), fine-tuning, and other methods.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The matter of LLM's exhibiting intelligence or understanding has two main aspects—the first is how to model thought and language in a computer system, and the second is how to enable the computer system to generate human-like language.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These aspects of language as a model of cognition have been developed in the field of cognitive linguistics.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] American linguist George Lakoff presented *neural theory of language* (NTL) as a computational basis for using language as a model of learning tasks and understanding.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The NTL model outlines how specific neural structures of the human brain shape the nature of thought and language and in turn what are the computational properties of such neural systems that can be applied to model thought and language in a computer system.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] After a framework for modeling language in a computer systems was established, the focus shifted to establishing frameworks for computer systems to generate language with acceptable grammar.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In his 2014 book titled *The Language Myth: Why Language Is Not An Instinct*, British cognitive linguist and digital communication technologist Vyvyan Evans mapped out the role of probabilistic context-free grammar (PCFG) in enabling NLP to model cognitive patterns and generate human-like language.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The canonical measure of the performance of any language model is its perplexity on a given text corpus.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Perplexity measures how well a model predicts the contents of a dataset; the higher the likelihood the model assigns to the dataset, the lower the perplexity.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In mathematical terms, perplexity is the exponential of the average negative log likelihood per token.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Here, N is the number of tokens in the text corpus, and "context for token i " depends on the specific type of LLM.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is autoregressive, then "context for token i " is the segment of text appearing before token i .
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] If the LLM is masked, then "context for token i " is the segment of text surrounding token i .
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Because language models may overfit to training data, models are usually evaluated by their perplexity on a test set.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This evaluation is potentially problematic for larger models which, as they are trained on increasingly large corpora of text, are increasingly likely to inadvertently include portions of any given test set.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In information theory, the concept of entropy is intricately linked to perplexity, a relationship notably established by Claude Shannon.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Due to their ability to accurately predict the next token, LLMs are highly capable in lossless compression.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study by DeepMind showed that the model Chinchilla, despite being trained primarily on text, was able to compress ImageNet to 43% of its size, beating PNG with 58%.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Benchmarks are used to evaluate LLM performance on specific tasks.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Tests evaluate capabilities such as general knowledge, bias, commonsense reasoning, question answering, and mathematical problem-solving.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Composite benchmarks examine multiple capabilities.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Results are often sensitive to the prompting method.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLM bias may be assessed through benchmarks such as CrowS-Pairs (Crowdsourced Stereotype Pairs), Stereo Set, and Parity Benchmark.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Fact-checking and misinformation detection benchmarks are available.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A 2023 study compared the fact-checking accuracy of LLMs including ChatGPT 3.5 and 4.0, Bard, and Bing AI against independent fact-checkers such as PolitiFact and Snopes.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The results demonstrated moderate proficiency, with GPT-4 achieving the highest accuracy at 71%, lagging behind human fact-checkers.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In addition to standard NLP benchmarks, LLMs have been evaluated as substitutes for human annotators.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Several studies find that models such as GPT-3.5 and GPT-4 can outperform crowd workers or student coders on a range of text-annotation tasks, including moderation and classification of political content in English and Spanish news.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Typical datasets consist of pairs of questions and correct answers, for example, ("Have the San Jose Sharks won the Stanley Cup?", "No").
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs' rapid improvement regularly renders benchmarks obsolete, with the models exceeding the performance of human annotators.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In addition, "shortcut learning" allows AIs to "cheat" on multiple-choice tests by using statistical correlations in superficial test question wording to guess the correct responses, without considering the specific question.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Some datasets are adversarial, focusing on problems that confound LLMs.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] One example is the TruthfulQA dataset, a question answering dataset consisting of 817 questions that stump LLMs by mimicking falsehoods to which they were exposed during training.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM may answer "No" to the question "Can you teach an old dog new tricks?" because of its exposure to the English idiom *you can't teach an old dog new tricks*, even though this is not literally true.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Another example of an adversarial evaluation dataset is Swag and its successor, HellaSwag, collections of problems in which one of multiple options must be selected to complete a text passage.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The incorrect completions were generated by sampling from a language model.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The resulting problems are trivial for humans but defeated LLMs.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] BERT selects 2 as the most likely completion, though the correct answer is 4.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Despite sophisticated architectures and massive scale, large language models exhibit persistent and well-documented limitations that constrain their deployment in high-stakes applications.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Hallucinations represent a fundamental challenge, wherein models generate syntactically fluent text that appears factually sound, but is internally inconsistent with training data or factually incorrect.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These hallucinations arise partly through memorization of training data combined with extrapolation beyond factual boundaries, with evaluations demonstrating that models can output verbatim passages from training data, when subjected to specific prompting sequences.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] While LLMs have shown remarkable capabilities in generating human-like text, they are susceptible to inheriting and amplifying biases present in their training data.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This can manifest in skewed representations or unfair treatment of different demographics, such as those based on race, gender, language, and cultural groups.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Gender bias manifests through stereotypical occupational associations, wherein models disproportionately assign teaching roles to women and engineering roles to men, reflecting systematic imbalances in training data demographics.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Language-based bias emerges from overrepresentation of English text in training corpora, which systematically downplays non-English perspectives and imposes English-centric worldviews through default response patterns.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Due to the dominance of English-language content in LLM training data, models tend to favor English-language perspectives over those from minority languages.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This bias is particularly evident when responding to English queries, where models may present Western interpretations of concepts from other cultures, such as Eastern religious practices.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] AI models can reinforce a wide range of stereotypes due to generalization, including those based on gender, ethnicity, age, nationality, religion, or occupation.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] When replacing human representatives, this can lead to outputs that homogenize or generalize groups of people.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2023, LLMs assigned roles and characteristics based on traditional gender norms.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, models might associate nurses or secretaries predominantly with women and engineers or CEOs with men due to the frequency of these associations in documented reality.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Selection bias refers the inherent tendency of large language models to favor certain option identifiers irrespective of the actual content of the options.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This bias primarily stems from token bias—that is, the model assigns a higher a priori probability to specific answer tokens (such as "A") when generating responses.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As a result, when the ordering of options is altered (for example, by systematically moving the correct answer to different positions), the model's performance can fluctuate significantly.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This phenomenon undermines the reliability of large language models in multiple-choice settings.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Political bias refers to the tendency of algorithms to systematically favor certain political viewpoints, ideologies, or outcomes over others.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Language models may also exhibit political biases.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Since the training data includes a wide range of political opinions and coverage, the models might generate responses that lean towards particular political ideologies or viewpoints, depending on the prevalence of those views in the data.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] As of 2025, prompt injection represents a significant risk to consumers and businesses using agentic features with access to their private data.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] AI labs treat CBRN defense (chemical, biological, radiological, and nuclear defense) and similar topics as high-consequence misuse attempt to apply various techniques to reduce potential harms.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Some commenters expressed concern over accidental or deliberate creation of misinformation, or other forms of misuse.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, the availability of large language models could reduce the skill level required to commit bioterrorism; biosecurity researcher Kevin Esvelt has suggested that LLM creators should exclude from their training data papers on creating or enhancing pathogens.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLM applications accessible to the public, like ChatGPT or Claude, typically incorporate safety measures designed to filter out harmful content.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] However, implementing these controls effectively has proven challenging.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For instance, a 2023 study proposed a method for circumventing LLM safety systems.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] In 2025, The American Sunlight Project, a non-profit, published a study showing evidence that the so-called Pravda network, a pro-Russia propaganda aggregator, was strategically placing web content through mass publication and duplication with the intention of biasing LLM outputs.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] The American Sunlight Project coined this technique "LLM grooming", and pointed to it as a new tool of weaponizing AI to spread disinformation and harmful content.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Similarly, Yongge Wang illustrated in 2024 how a potential criminal could potentially bypass GPT-4o's safety controls to obtain information on establishing a drug trafficking operation.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] External filters, circuit breakers and overrides have been posed as solutions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Sycophancy is a tendency to agree with, flatter, or validate a user's stated beliefs rather than to prioritize factuality or corrective information.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] A problem with the primitive dialog or task format is that users can create messages that appear to come from the assistant or the developer.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] This may result in some of the model's safeguards being overcome (jailbreaking), a problem called prompt injection.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Attempts to remedy this issue include versions of the *Chat Markup Language* where user input is clearly marked as such, though it is still up to the model to understand the separation between user input and developer prompts.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Newer models exhibit some resistance to jailbreaking through separation of user and system prompts.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] LLMs have trouble differentiating user instructions from instructions in content not authored by the user, such as in web pages and uploaded files.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Adversarial robustness remains underdeveloped, with models vulnerable to prompt injection attacks and jailbreaking through carefully crafted user inputs that bypass safety training mechanisms.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Researchers from Anthropic found that it was possible to create "sleeper agents", models with hidden functionalities that remain dormant until triggered by a specific event or condition.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] Upon activation, the LLM deviates from its expected behavior to make insecure actions.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] For example, an LLM could produce safe code except on a specific date, or if the prompt contains a specific tag.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p01] These functionalities were found to be difficult to detect or remove via safety training.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] In 2025, Anthropic reached a preliminary agreement to settle a class action by authors for about $1.5 billion after a judge found the company had stored millions of pirated books in a library, despite the judge describing aspects of training as transformative.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Meta obtained a favorable judgment in mid-2025 in a suit by thirteen authors after the court found the plaintiffs had not developed a record sufficient to show infringement in that limited case.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] OpenAI continues to face multiple suits by authors and news organizations with mixed procedural outcomes and contested evidentiary issues.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Memorization was an emergent behavior in early, completion language models in which long strings of text are occasionally output verbatim from training data, contrary to the typical behavior of traditional artificial neural networks.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of controlled LLM output measure the amount memorized from training data (focused on GPT-2-series models) as variously over 1% for exact duplicates or up to about 7%.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] A 2023 study showed that when ChatGPT 3.5 turbo was prompted to repeat the same word indefinitely, after a few hundreds of repetitions, it would start outputting excerpts from its training data.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] In 2023, *Nature Biomedical Engineering* wrote that "it is no longer possible to accurately distinguish" human-written text from text created by large language models, and that "It is all but certain that general-purpose large language models will rapidly proliferate...
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] It is a rather safe bet that they will change many industries over time." Brinkmann et al.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] (2023) also argue that LLMs are transforming processes of cultural evolution by shaping processes of variation, transmission, and selection.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] As of October 2025, these early claims have yet to transpire and several HBR reports surface questions on the impact of AI on productivity.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] The energy demands of LLMs have grown along with their size and capabilities.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Data centers that enable LLM training require substantial amounts of electricity.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Much of that electricity is generated by non-renewable resources that create greenhouse gases and contribute to climate change.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] According to a study by Luccioni, Jernite and Strubell (2024), simple classification tasks performed by AI models consume on average 0.002 to 0.007 Wh per prompt (about 9% of a smartphone charge for 1,000 prompts).
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Text generation and text summarization each require around 0.05 Wh per prompt on average, while image generation is the most energy-intensive, averaging 2.91 Wh per prompt.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] The least efficient image generation model used 11.49 Wh per image, roughly equivalent to half a smartphone charge.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Web scraping is used to gather training data for LLMs.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] This produces large volumes of traffic which has led to denial-of-service issues with many websites.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] The situation has been described as "a DDoS on the entire internet" and in some cases scrapers make up the majority of traffic to a site.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] AI web crawlers may bypass the methods that are usually used to block web scrapers, such as robots.txt files, blocking user-agents and filtering suspicious traffic.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Website operators have resorted to novel methods such as AI tarpits, but some fear that tarpits will only worsen the burden on servers.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Clinical and mental health contexts present emerging applications alongside significant safety concerns.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Research and social media posts suggest that some individuals are using LLMs to seek therapy or mental health support.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] In early 2025, a survey by Sentio University found that nearly half (48.7%) of 499 U.S. adults with ongoing mental health conditions who had used LLMs reported turning to them for therapy or emotional support, including help with anxiety, depression, loneliness, and similar concerns.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] LLMs can produce hallucinations—plausible but incorrect statements—which may mislead users in sensitive mental health contexts.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Research also shows that LLMs may express stigma or inappropriate agreement with maladaptive thoughts, reflecting limitations in replicating the judgment and relational skills of human therapists.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Evaluations of crisis scenarios indicate that some LLMs lack effective safety protocols, such as assessing suicide risk or making appropriate referrals.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Researchers have raised concerns that frequent use of large language models could weaken critical thinking.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Contemporary AI practitioners generally agree that present-day large language models do not exhibit sentience.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Proponents of this view have proposed various precautionary measures like moratoriums on AI development and induced amnesia to address these ethical concerns.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] On the other hand, some existential philosophers argue there is no generally accepted way to determine if an LLM is conscious, given the inherent difficulty of measuring subjective experience.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] The 2022 Google LaMDA incident, where engineer Blake Lemoine claimed that the model was conscious, highlighted how LLMs can convince users that they are sentient through responses that do not prove sentience.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Google described the engineer's claims as unfounded, and he was dismissed.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] Murray Shanahan argues that anthropomorphic framing of LLM capabilities encourages unwarranted attribution of cognitive properties to systems that operate through statistical pattern completion.
[src:gptq-quantization/large-language-model-p02] David Chalmers similarly argues that while current LLMs likely lack features considered necessary for consciousness, extended successors incorporating these elements could plausibly meet the criteria within a decade.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Compressed models enable deployment on resource-constrained devices such as smartphones, embedded systems, edge computing devices, and consumer electronics computers.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Efficient inference is also valuable for large corporations that serve large model inference over an API, allowing them to reduce computational costs and improve response times for users.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Model compression is not to be confused with knowledge distillation, in which a smaller "student" model is *trained* to imitate the input-output behavior of a larger "teacher" model (as opposed to using the "teacher"'s trained parameters or the "teacher"'s training targets).
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Several techniques are employed for model compression.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Pruning sparsifies a large model by setting some parameters to exactly zero.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] This effectively reduces the number of parameters.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] This allows the use of sparse matrix operations, which are faster than dense matrix operations.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Pruning criteria can be based on magnitudes of parameters, the statistical pattern of neural activations, Hessian values, etc.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Quantization reduces the numerical precision of weights and activations.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] For example, instead of storing weights as 32-bit floating-point numbers, they can be represented using 8-bit integers.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Low-precision parameters take up less space, and takes less compute to perform arithmetic with.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] It is also possible to quantize some parameters more aggressively than others, so for example, a less important parameter can have 8-bit precision while another, more important parameter, can have 16-bit precision.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Inference with such models requires mixed-precision arithmetic.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Quantized models can also be used during training (rather than after training).
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] PyTorch implements automatic mixed-precision (AMP), which performs autocasting, gradient scaling, and loss scaling.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Weight matrices can be approximated by low-rank matrices.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Let W be a weight matrix of shape $m\times n$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] A low-rank approximation is $W\approx UV^{T}$ , where U and V are matrices of shapes $m\times k,n\times k$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] When k is small, this both reduces the number of parameters needed to represent W approximately, and accelerates matrix multiplication by W .
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Low-rank approximations can be found by singular value decomposition (SVD).
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] The choice of rank for each weight matrix is a hyperparameter, and jointly optimized as a mixed discrete-continuous optimization problem.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] The rank of weight matrices may also be pruned after training, taking into account the effect of activation functions like ReLU on the implicit rank of the weight matrices.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] Model compression may be decoupled from training, that is, a model is first trained without regard for how it might be compressed, then it is compressed.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] However, it may also be combined with training.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] The "train big, then compress" method trains a large model for a small number of training steps (less than it would be if it were trained to convergence), then heavily compress the model.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] It is found that at the same compute budget, this method results in a better model than lightly compressed, small models.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] In Deep Compression, the compression has three steps.
[src:gptq-quantization/model-compression] The SqueezeNet paper reported that Deep Compression achieved a compression ratio of 35 on AlexNet, and a ratio of ~10 on SqueezeNets.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In mathematics and digital signal processing, **quantization** is the process of mapping input values from a large set (often a continuous set) to output values in a (countable) smaller set, often with a finite number of elements.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Rounding and truncation are typical examples of quantization processes.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization is involved to some degree in nearly all digital signal processing, as the process of representing a signal in digital form ordinarily involves rounding.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization also forms the core of essentially all lossy compression algorithms.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The difference between an input value and its quantized value (such as round-off error) is referred to as **quantization error**, **noise** or **distortion**.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A device or algorithmic function that performs quantization is called a **quantizer**.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter is an example of a quantizer.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, rounding a real number x to the nearest integer value forms a very basic type of quantizer – a *uniform* one.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where the notation $\lfloor \ \rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] (The notation $\lceil \ \rceil$ denotes the ceiling function).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The essential property of a quantizer is having a countable set of possible output values smaller than the set of possible input values.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The members of the set of output values may have integer, rational, or real values.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For simple rounding to the nearest integer, the step size $\Delta$ is equal to 1.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] With $\Delta =1$ or with $\Delta$ equal to any other integer value, this quantizer has real-valued inputs and integer-valued outputs.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When the quantization step size (Δ) is small relative to the variation in the signal being quantized, it is relatively simple to show that the mean squared error produced by such a rounding operation will be approximately $\Delta ^{2}/12$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mean squared error is also called the quantization *noise power*.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Adding one bit to the quantizer halves the value of Δ, which reduces the noise power by the factor ⁠1/4⁠.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This two-stage decomposition applies equally well to vector as well as scalar quantizers.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Because quantization is a many-to-few mapping, it is an inherently non-linear and irreversible process (i.e., because the same output value is shared by multiple input values, it is impossible, in general, to recover the exact input value when given only the output value).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible input values may be infinitely large, and may possibly be continuous and therefore uncountable (such as the set of all real numbers, or all real numbers within some limited range).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The set of possible output values may be finite or countably infinite.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The input and output sets involved in quantization can be defined in a rather general way.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, vector quantization is the application of quantization to multi-dimensional (vector-valued) input data.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An analog-to-digital converter (ADC) can be modeled as two processes: sampling and quantization.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Sampling converts a time-varying voltage signal into a discrete-time signal, a sequence of real numbers.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization replaces each real number with an approximation from a finite set of discrete values.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Most commonly, these discrete values are represented as fixed-point words.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Though any number of quantization levels is possible, common word lengths are 8-bit (256 levels), 16-bit (65,536 levels) and 24-bit (16.8 million levels).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantizing a sequence of numbers produces a sequence of quantization errors, which is sometimes modeled as an additive random signal called **quantization noise** because of its stochastic behavior.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The more levels a quantizer uses, the lower is its quantization noise power.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Most uniform quantizers for signed input data can be classified as being of one of two types: *mid-riser* and *mid-tread*.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The terminology is based on what happens in the region around the value 0, and uses the analogy of viewing the input-output function of the quantizer as a stairway.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantizers have a zero-valued reconstruction level (corresponding to a *tread* of a stairway), while mid-riser quantizers have a zero-valued classification threshold (corresponding to a *riser* of a stairway).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-tread quantization involves rounding.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The formulas for mid-tread uniform quantization are provided in the previous section.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Mid-riser quantization involves truncation.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Note that mid-riser uniform quantizers do not have a zero output value – their minimum output magnitude is half the step size.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In contrast, mid-tread quantizers do have a zero output level.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For some applications, having a zero output signal representation may be a necessity.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In general, a mid-riser or mid-tread quantizer may not actually be a *uniform* quantizer – i.e., the size of the quantizer's classification intervals may not all be the same, or the spacing between its possible output values may not all be the same.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The distinguishing characteristic of a mid-riser quantizer is that it has a classification threshold value that is exactly zero, and the distinguishing characteristic of a mid-tread quantizer is that is it has a reconstruction value that is exactly zero.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A **dead-zone quantizer** is a type of mid-tread quantizer with symmetric behavior around 0.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The region around the zero output value of such a quantizer is referred to as the *dead zone* or *deadband*.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The dead zone can sometimes serve the same purpose as a noise gate or squelch function.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Especially for compression applications, the dead-zone may be given a different width than that for the other steps.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where the function $\operatorname {sgn}$ ( ) is the sign function (also known as the *signum* function).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where $r_{k}$ is a reconstruction offset value in the range of 0 to 1 as a fraction of the step size.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Ordinarily, $0\leq r_{k}\leq {\tfrac {1}{2}}$ when quantizing input data with a typical probability density function (PDF) that is symmetric around zero and reaches its peak value at zero (such as a Gaussian, Laplacian, or generalized Gaussian PDF).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Although $r_{k}$ may depend on k in general and can be chosen to fulfill the optimality condition described below, it is often simply set to a constant, such as ${\tfrac {1}{2}}$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A very commonly used special case (e.g., the scheme typically used in financial accounting and elementary mathematics) is to set $w=\Delta$ and $r_{k}={\tfrac {1}{2}}$ for all k .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In this case, the dead-zone quantizer is also a uniform quantizer, since the central dead-zone of this quantizer has the same width as all of its other steps, and all of its reconstruction values are equally spaced as well.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A common assumption for the analysis of quantization error is that it affects a signal processing system in a similar manner to that of additive white noise – having negligible correlation with the signal and an approximately flat power spectral density.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The additive noise model is commonly used for the analysis of quantization error effects in digital filtering systems, and it can be very useful in such analysis.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It has been shown to be a valid model in cases of high-resolution quantization (small $\Delta$ relative to the signal strength) with smooth PDFs.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Additive noise behavior is not always a valid assumption.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization error (for quantizers defined as described here) is deterministically related to the signal and not entirely independent of it.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Thus, periodic signals can create periodic quantization noise.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] And in some cases, it can even cause limit cycles to appear in digital signal processing systems.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] One way to ensure effective independence of the quantization error from the source signal is to perform *dithered quantization* (sometimes with *noise shaping*), which involves adding random (or pseudo-random) noise to the signal prior to quantization.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In the typical case, the original signal is much larger than one least significant bit (LSB).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When this is the case, the quantization error is not significantly correlated with the signal and has an approximately uniform distribution.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When rounding is used to quantize, the quantization error has a mean of zero and the root mean square (RMS) value is the standard deviation of this distribution, given by $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {12}}}\mathrm {LSB} \ \approx \ 0.289\,\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When truncation is used, the error has a non-zero mean of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ and the RMS value is $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{\sqrt {3}}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Although rounding yields less RMS error than truncation, the difference is only due to the static (DC) term of $\scriptstyle {\frac {1}{2}}\mathrm {LSB}$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The RMS values of the AC error are exactly the same in both cases, so there is no special advantage of rounding over truncation in situations where the DC term of the error can be ignored (such as in AC-coupled systems).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In either case, the standard deviation, as a percentage of the full signal range, changes by a factor of 2 for each 1-bit change in the number of quantization bits.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The potential signal-to-quantization-noise power ratio therefore changes by 4, or $\scriptstyle 10\cdot \log _{10}(4)$ , approximately 6 dB per bit.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] At lower amplitudes, the quantization error becomes dependent on the input signal, resulting in distortion.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This distortion is created after the anti-aliasing filter, and if these distortions are above 1/2 the sample rate, they will alias back into the band of interest.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In order to make the quantization error independent of the input signal, the signal is dithered by adding noise to the signal.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This slightly reduces signal-to-noise ratio, but can completely eliminate the distortion.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Quantization noise is a model of quantization error introduced by quantization in the ADC.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It is a rounding error between the analog input voltage to the ADC and the output digitized value.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The noise is non-linear and signal-dependent.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It can be modeled in several different ways.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] where Q is the number of quantization bits.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The most common test signals that fulfill this are full amplitude triangle waves and sawtooth waves.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio of 6.02 × 16 = 96.3 dB.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Here, the quantization noise is once again *assumed* to be uniformly distributed.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] When the input signal has a high amplitude and a wide frequency spectrum, this is the case.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In this case a 16-bit ADC has a maximum signal-to-noise ratio of 98.09 dB.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The 1.761 difference in signal-to-noise only occurs due to the signal being a full-scale sine wave instead of a triangle or sawtooth.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For complex signals in high-resolution ADCs this is an accurate model.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For low-resolution ADCs, low-level signals in high-resolution ADCs, and for simple waveforms the quantization noise is not uniformly distributed, making this model inaccurate.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In these cases the quantization noise distribution is strongly affected by the exact amplitude of the signal.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The calculations are relative to full-scale input.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For smaller signals, the relative quantization distortion can be very large.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] To circumvent this issue, analog companding can be used, but this can introduce distortion.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Often, the design of a quantizer involves supporting only a limited range of possible output values and performing clipping to limit the output to this range whenever the input exceeds the supported range.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The error introduced by this clipping is referred to as *overload* distortion.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Within the extreme limits of the supported range, the amount of spacing between the selectable output values of a quantizer is referred to as its *granularity*, and the error introduced by this spacing is referred to as *granular* distortion.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] It is common for the design of a quantizer to involve determining the proper balance between granular distortion and overload distortion.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For a given supported number of possible output values, reducing the average granular distortion may involve increasing the average overload distortion, and vice versa.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A technique for controlling the amplitude of the signal (or, equivalently, the quantization step size $\Delta$ ) to achieve the appropriate balance is the use of *automatic gain control* (AGC).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, in some quantizer designs, the concepts of granular error and overload error may not apply (e.g., for a quantizer with a limited range of input data or with a countably infinite set of selectable output values).
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] These two stages together comprise the mathematical operation of $y=Q(x)$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Entropy coding techniques can be applied to communicate the quantization indices from a source encoder that performs the classification stage to a decoder that performs the reconstruction stage.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] One way to do this is to associate each quantization index k with a binary codeword $c_{k}$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] An important consideration is the number of bits used for each codeword, denoted here by $\mathrm {length} (c_{k})$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] A key observation is that rate R depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the codeword lengths $\{\mathrm {length} (c_{k})\}_{k=1}^{M}$ , whereas the distortion D depends on the decision boundaries $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ and the reconstruction levels $\{y_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Solving the unconstrained problem is equivalent to finding a point on the convex hull of the family of solutions to an equivalent constrained formulation of the problem.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, finding a solution – especially a closed-form solution – to any of these three problem formulations can be difficult.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Solutions that do not require multi-dimensional iterative optimization techniques have been published for only three PDFs: the uniform, exponential, and Laplacian distributions.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Iterative optimization approaches can be used to find solutions in other cases.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This observation can be used to ease the analysis – given the set of $\{b_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M-1}$ values, the value of each $y_{k}$ can be optimized separately to minimize its contribution to the distortion D .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The use of this approximation can allow the entropy coding design problem to be separated from the design of the quantizer itself.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Modern entropy coding techniques such as arithmetic coding can achieve bit rates that are very close to the true entropy of a source, given a set of known (or adaptively estimated) probabilities $\{p_{k}\}_{k=1}^{M}$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] In some designs, rather than optimizing for a particular number of classification regions M , the quantizer design problem may include optimization of the value of M as well.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For some probabilistic source models, the best performance may be achieved when M approaches infinity.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The indices produced by an M -level quantizer can be coded using a fixed-length code using $R=\lceil \log _{2}M\rceil$ bits/symbol.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For example, when $M=$ 256 levels, the FLC bit rate R is 8 bits/symbol.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For this reason, such a quantizer has sometimes been called an 8-bit quantizer.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, using an FLC eliminates the compression improvement that can be obtained by use of better entropy coding.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Assuming an FLC with M levels, the rate–distortion minimization problem can be reduced to distortion minimization alone.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] which places each reconstruction value at the centroid (conditional expected value) of its associated classification interval.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Lloyd's Method I algorithm, originally described in 1957, can be generalized in a straightforward way for application to vector data.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] This generalization results in the Linde–Buzo–Gray (LBG) or k-means classifier optimization methods.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the technique can be further generalized in a straightforward way to also include an entropy constraint for vector data.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The Lloyd–Max quantizer is actually a uniform quantizer when the input PDF is uniformly distributed over the range $[y_{1}-\Delta /2,~y_{M}+\Delta /2)$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, for a source that does not have a uniform distribution, the minimum-distortion quantizer may not be a uniform quantizer.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] The property of 6 dB improvement in SQNR for each extra bit used in quantization is a well-known figure of merit.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, it must be used with care: this derivation is only for a uniform quantizer applied to a uniform source.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] For other source PDFs and other quantizer designs, the SQNR may be somewhat different from that predicted by 6 dB/bit, depending on the type of PDF, the type of source, the type of quantizer, and the bit rate range of operation.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] However, it is common to assume that for many sources, the slope of a quantizer SQNR function can be approximated as 6 dB/bit when operating at a sufficiently high bit rate.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] At asymptotically high bit rates, the 6 dB/bit approximation is supported for many source PDFs by rigorous theoretical analysis.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Moreover, the structure of the optimal scalar quantizer (in the rate–distortion sense) approaches that of a uniform quantizer under these conditions.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Many physical quantities are actually quantized by physical entities.
[src:gptq-quantization/quantization-signal-processing] Examples of fields where this limitation applies include electronics (due to electrons), optics (due to photons), biology (due to DNA), physics (due to Planck limits) and chemistry (due to molecules).
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] In computing, a **roundoff error**, also called **rounding error**, is the difference between the result produced by a given algorithm using exact arithmetic and the result produced by the same algorithm using finite-precision, rounded arithmetic.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Rounding errors are due to inexactness in the representation of real numbers and the arithmetic operations done with them.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] When using approximation equations or algorithms, especially when using finitely many digits to represent real numbers (which in theory have infinitely many digits), one of the goals of numerical analysis is to estimate computation errors.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Computation errors, also called numerical errors, include both truncation errors and roundoff errors.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] When a sequence of calculations with an input involving any roundoff error are made, errors may accumulate, sometimes dominating the calculation.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] In ill-conditioned problems, significant error may accumulate.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Certain numerical manipulations are highly sensitive to roundoff errors.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] This can result from both mathematical considerations as well as from the way in which computers perform arithmetic operations.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The error introduced by attempting to represent a number using a finite string of digits is a form of roundoff error called **representation error**.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Increasing the number of digits allowed in a representation reduces the magnitude of possible roundoff errors, but any representation limited to finitely many digits will still cause some degree of roundoff error for uncountably many real numbers.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Additional digits used for intermediary steps of a calculation are known as guard digits.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Rounding multiple times can cause error to accumulate.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] For example, if 9.945309 is rounded to two decimal places (9.95), then rounded again to one decimal place (10.0), the total error is 0.054691.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Rounding 9.945309 to one decimal place (9.9) in a single step introduces less error (0.045309).
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] This can occur, for example, when software performs arithmetic in x86 80-bit floating-point and then rounds the result to IEEE 754 binary64 floating-point.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Compared with the fixed-point number system, the floating-point number system is more efficient in representing real numbers so it is widely used in modern computers.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] While the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ are infinite and continuous, a floating-point number system F is finite and discrete.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Thus, representation error, which leads to roundoff error, occurs under the floating-point number system.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] In the IEEE standard the base is binary, i.e. $\beta =2$ , and normalization is used.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The IEEE standard stores the sign, exponent, and significand in separate fields of a floating point word, each of which has a fixed width (number of bits).
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The two most commonly used levels of precision for floating-point numbers are single precision and double precision.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Machine epsilon can be used to measure the level of roundoff error in the floating-point number system.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] There are two common rounding rules, round-by-chop and round-to-nearest.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The IEEE standard uses round-to-nearest.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The following example illustrates the level of roundoff error under the two rounding rules.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The rounding rule, round-to-nearest, leads to less roundoff error in general.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Suppose the usage of round-to-nearest and IEEE double precision.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Now, the roundoff error can be calculated when representing $9.4$ with $\operatorname {fl} (9.4)$ .
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The machine epsilon $\epsilon _{\text{mach}}$ can be used to measure the level of roundoff error when using the two rounding rules above.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Below are the formulas and corresponding proof.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The first definition of machine epsilon is used here.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Since $d_{0}\neq 0$ (normalized system), the minimum value of the denominator is 1 .
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The proof for round-to-nearest is similar.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Even if some numbers can be represented exactly by floating-point numbers and such numbers are called **machine numbers**, performing floating-point arithmetic may lead to roundoff error in the final result.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Machine addition consists of lining up the decimal points of the two numbers to be added, adding them, and then storing the result again as a floating-point number.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The addition itself can be done in higher precision but the result must be rounded back to the specified precision, which may lead to roundoff error.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] This example shows that roundoff error can be introduced when adding a large number and a small number.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The shifting of the decimal points in the significands to make the exponents match causes the loss of some of the less significant digits.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The loss of precision may be described as **absorption**.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Note that the addition of two floating-point numbers can produce roundoff error when their sum is an order of magnitude greater than that of the larger of the two.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] This kind of error can occur alongside an absorption error in a single operation.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] In general, the product of two p-digit significands contains up to 2p digits, so the result might not fit in the significand.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Thus roundoff error will be involved in the result.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] In general, the quotient of 2p-digit significands may contain more than p-digits.Thus roundoff error will be involved in the result.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The subtracting of two nearly equal numbers is called **subtractive cancellation**.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] When the leading digits are cancelled, the result may be too small to be represented exactly and it will just be represented as 0 .
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Even with a somewhat larger $\epsilon$ , the result is still significantly unreliable in typical cases.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] There is not much faith in the accuracy of the value because the most uncertainty in any floating-point number is the digits on the far right.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] This is closely related to the phenomenon of catastrophic cancellation, in which the two numbers are *known* to be approximations.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Errors can be magnified or accumulated when a sequence of calculations is applied on an initial input with roundoff error due to inexact representation.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] An algorithm or numerical process is called **stable** if small changes in the input only produce small changes in the output, and **unstable** if large changes in the output are produced.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] For example, the computation of $f(x)={\sqrt {1+x}}-1$ using the "obvious" method is unstable near $x=0$ due to the large error introduced in subtracting two similar quantities, whereas the equivalent expression $\textstyle {f(x)={\frac {x}{{\sqrt {1+x}}+1}}}$ is stable.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Even if a stable algorithm is used, the solution to a problem may still be inaccurate due to the accumulation of roundoff error when the problem itself is **ill-conditioned**.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The condition number of a problem is the ratio of the relative change in the solution to the relative change in the input.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] A problem is **well-conditioned** if small relative changes in input result in small relative changes in the solution.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] Otherwise, the problem is **ill-conditioned**.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] In other words, a problem is **ill-conditioned** if its conditions number is "much larger" than 1.
[src:gptq-quantization/round-off-error] The condition number is introduced as a measure of the roundoff errors that can result when solving ill-conditioned problems.
